05092nam a22007095i 9781478009221DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019024075  a97814780092217 a10.1515/97814780092212doi  a(DE-B1597)553746  a(OCoLC)1114279758  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aPN1992.2 4aPN1992.2b.G35 2020 7aPER0100302bisacsh04a385.44092231 aGalili, Doron, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSeeing by Electricity :bThe Emergence of Television, 1878-1939 /cDoron Galili. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSign, Storage, Transmission00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. Archaeologies of Moving Image Transmission -- t1 Ancient Affiliates: The Nineteenth-Century Origins of Cinema and Television -- t2 Severed Eyeballs and Prolonged Optic Nerves: Television as Modern Prosthetic Vision -- t3 Happy Combinations of Electricity and Photography: Moving Image Transmission in the Early Cinema Era -- tPART II Debating the Specificity of Television, On-and Off-Screen -- t4 Cinema's Radio Double: Hollywood Comes to Terms with Television -- t5 "We Must Prepare!": Dziga Vertov and the Avant-Garde Reception of Television -- t6 Thinking across Media: Classical Film Theory's Encounter with Television -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlready in the late nineteenth century, electricians, physicists, and telegraph technicians dreamed of inventing televisual communication apparatuses that would "see" by electricity as a means of extending human perception. In Seeing by Electricity Doron Galili traces the early history of television, from fantastical image transmission devices initially imagined in the 1870s such as the Telectroscope, the Phantoscope, and the Distant Seer to the emergence of broadcast television in the 1930s. Galili examines how televisual technologies were understood in relation to film at different cultural moments-whether as a perfection of cinema, a threat to the Hollywood industry, or an alternative medium for avant-garde experimentation. Highlighting points of overlap and divergence in the histories of television and cinema, Galili demonstrates that the intermedial relationship between the two media did not start with their economic and institutional rivalry of the late 1940s but rather goes back to their very origins. In so doing, he brings film studies and television studies together in ways that advance contemporary debates in media theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aMotion picturesxHistoryy20th century. 0aTelevision broadcastingxHistoryy20th century. 0aTelevisionxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertArt and Architecture eBook-Package 2020z978311073823008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069631808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2020z9783110704655oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2020 Englishz978311070478508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478009221zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478009221423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478009221.j